  "title": "Der Dativ",
  "subtitle": "Indirect objects, dative prepositions, and dative verbs",
  "focus": ["Dativ", "Indirect Objects", "Dative Prepositions"],
  "conceptSections": [
    {
      "id": "gf6-concept-1",
      "heading": "What the dative marks",
      "explanation": "The dative case marks the indirect object â€” the recipient or beneficiary of an action. In a sentence with both a direct and indirect object, the indirect object is in the dative. Think of it as the person who receives something.",
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich gebe dem Kind ein Buch.", "en": "I give the child a book.", "note": "dem Kind = dative (recipient), ein Buch = accusative (thing given)" },
        { "de": "Sie zeigt der Frau den Weg.", "en": "She shows the woman the way.", "note": "der Frau = dative (recipient), den Weg = accusative" },
        { "de": "Er schreibt seinem Freund eine Nachricht.", "en": "He writes his friend a message.", "note": "seinem Freund = dative (recipient)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf6-concept-2",
      "heading": "Dative article changes",
      "explanation": "All genders change their articles in the dative. The plural adds an -n to most nouns (unless they already end in -n or -s).",
      "table": {
        "headers": ["Gender", "Nominativ", "Dativ", "Indefinit Dativ", "Negativ Dativ"],
        "rows": [
          ["Masculine", "der", "dem", "einem", "keinem"],
          ["Neuter", "das", "dem", "einem", "keinem"],
          ["Feminine", "die", "der", "einer", "keiner"],
          ["Plural", "die", "den (+n)", "â€”", "keinen (+n)"]
        ]
      },
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich helfe dem Mann.", "en": "I help the man.", "note": "masc: der â†’ dem" },
        { "de": "Sie gibt dem Kind Schokolade.", "en": "She gives the child chocolate.", "note": "neuter: das â†’ dem" },
        { "de": "Er dankt der Lehrerin.", "en": "He thanks the teacher (f).", "note": "fem: die â†’ der" },
        { "de": "Ich schreibe den Kindern einen Brief.", "en": "I write the children a letter.", "note": "plural: die â†’ den + n on noun" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf6-concept-3",
      "heading": "Dative personal pronouns",
      "explanation": "When the indirect object is a pronoun, use the dative pronoun forms.",
      "table": {
        "headers": ["Nominativ", "Akkusativ", "Dativ", "English (Dativ)"],
        "rows": [
          ["ich", "mich", "mir", "to/for me"],
          ["du", "dich", "dir", "to/for you"],
          ["er", "ihn", "ihm", "to/for him"],
          ["es", "es", "ihm", "to/for it"],
          ["sie", "sie", "ihr", "to/for her"],
          ["wir", "uns", "uns", "to/for us"],
          ["ihr", "euch", "euch", "to/for you (pl.)"],
          ["sie/Sie", "sie/Sie", "ihnen/Ihnen", "to/for them/you"]
        ]
      },
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Kannst du mir helfen?", "en": "Can you help me?", "note": "ich â†’ mir" },
        { "de": "Ich gebe dir das Buch.", "en": "I give you the book.", "note": "du â†’ dir" },
        { "de": "Er schreibt ihm eine Nachricht.", "en": "He writes him a message.", "note": "er â†’ ihm" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf6-concept-4",
      "heading": "Dative prepositions",
      "explanation": "These 8 prepositions ALWAYS take the dative case. Memorise them as a fixed group.",
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich komme aus der Schweiz.", "en": "I come from Switzerland.", "note": "aus = from (origin)" },
        { "de": "Er wohnt bei seiner Mutter.", "en": "He lives at his mother's.", "note": "bei = at, near, with" },
        { "de": "Ich fahre mit dem Bus.", "en": "I travel by bus.", "note": "mit = with, by" },
        { "de": "Nach dem Essen gehe ich spazieren.", "en": "After eating I go for a walk.", "note": "nach = after, to (cities/countries)" },
        { "de": "Seit einem Jahr lerne ich Deutsch.", "en": "I have been learning German for a year.", "note": "seit = since, for (time)" },
        { "de": "Das Geschenk ist von meinem Bruder.", "en": "The gift is from my brother.", "note": "von = from, of" },
        { "de": "Ich gehe zum Arzt.", "en": "I go to the doctor.", "note": "zu = to (people, places) â€” zum = zu dem" },
        { "de": "Das CafÃ© ist gegenÃ¼ber dem Bahnhof.", "en": "The cafÃ© is opposite the station.", "note": "gegenÃ¼ber = opposite" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf6-concept-5",
      "heading": "Verbs that take a dative object",
      "explanation": "Some verbs take a dative object instead of (or in addition to) an accusative one. These must be learned individually.",
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich helfe dir gern.", "en": "I'm happy to help you.", "note": "helfen + dative" },
        { "de": "Das Kleid gefÃ¤llt mir.", "en": "I like the dress. (lit: The dress pleases me.)", "note": "gefallen + dative" },
        { "de": "Das Buch gehÃ¶rt dem Lehrer.", "en": "The book belongs to the teacher.", "note": "gehÃ¶ren + dative" },
        { "de": "Die Schuhe passen mir nicht.", "en": "The shoes don't fit me.", "note": "passen + dative" },
        { "de": "Die Suppe schmeckt den Kindern.", "en": "The children like the soup. (lit: The soup tastes good to the children.)", "note": "schmecken + dative" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf6-concept-6",
      "heading": "Location prepositions with dative (Wo?)",
      "explanation": "Two-way prepositions (in, an, auf, etc.) take the dative when answering the question 'Wo?' (Where?). Common contractions: in dem = im, an dem = am.",
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich bin im Supermarkt.", "en": "I am in the supermarket.", "note": "im = in dem (Wo? â†’ dative)" },
        { "de": "Das Bild hÃ¤ngt an der Wand.", "en": "The picture hangs on the wall.", "note": "an der Wand = dative (location)" },
        { "de": "Wir sitzen am Tisch.", "en": "We are sitting at the table.", "note": "am = an dem" }
      ]
    }
  ],
